solutions.content:
There are a few situations:
- A and B are with different lengths => false
- length < 2 => can't swap, false
- only 1 or more than 2 unmatched indexes => false
- exactly 2 unmatched indexes, becomes the same after swap => true
- A and B are identical, and exists at least 1 letter appeared more than once in each string => true

Update 2: I have improved it further! Now version 3 is about 3 times faster than version 1 on long strings, based on my benchmark. And there's no any extra data structures used (set, string, array, etc.) You can even replace the bitset with an int and it will just work (but the code will be messier, see below)
Explain:
- We know `0 ^ x = x` and `x ^ x = 0`, if `x != y` then `x ^ y != 0`. So if we found `(x, y)` in string A and `(y, x)` in string B, `(x ^ y) ^ (y ^ x) == 0`. There is one exception: if we found `(x, x)` in string A and `(y, y)` in string B, `(x ^ x) ^ (y ^ y)` is also `0`, so we have to check the 2 letters found in same string `(x1, x2)` are not the same - `x1 & x2 != 0`.
- We are garanteed to be able to find duplicated letters within the first 27 letters, so don't bother to do the checks if we have already found any.
#### Version 3
```cpp
bool buddyStrings(string A, string B) {
	if (A.size() != B.size() || A.size() < 2) return false;
	bitset<128> bits{0};
	uint8_t m1 = 0, m2 = 0, count = 0, dup = 0;
	for (int i = 0; i < A.size() && count <= 2; ++i) {
		if (A[i] != B[i]) m1 ^= A[i] ^ B[i], m2 ^= A[i], ++count;
		if (!dup) dup = bits.test(A[i]), bits.set(A[i]);
	}
	return (count == 2 && !m1 && m2) || (!count && dup);
}
```
### Version 3 ints only
```cpp
bool buddyStrings(string A, string B) {
	if (A.size() != B.size() || A.size() < 2) return false;
	uint32_t bits = 0, m1 = 0, m2 = 0, count = 0, dup = 0;
	for (int i = 0; i < A.size() && count <= 2; ++i) {
		if (A[i] != B[i]) m1 ^= A[i] ^ B[i], m2 ^= A[i], ++count;
		if (!dup) dup = bits & (1 << (A[i] - 'a')), bits |= (1 << (A[i] - 'a'));
	}
	return (count == 2 && !m1 && m2) || (!count && dup);
}
```
