#### 1st approach

Here was my first approach using the way I solved [#921](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid) 
Not the best but easy to come up with if you solved similar problem e.g. [#921](https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-add-to-make-parentheses-valid) [#20](https://leetcode.com/problems/valid-parentheses)  

```py
"""
    1st: stack + hashtable
    - similar to lc921 but save the indices of the redundant opens & closes
    - construct the result by removing the characters at redundant indices
    - 12 lines

    Time    O(3N)
    Space   O(N)
    164 ms, faster than 79.33%
"""
class Solution(object):
    def minRemoveToMakeValid(self, s):
        opens, closes = [], []
        for i in range(len(s)):
            c = s[i]
            if c == '(':
                opens.append(i)
            elif c == ')':
                if len(opens) == 0:
                    closes.append(i)
                else:
                    opens.pop()
        hs = set(opens+closes)
        return ''.join(s[i] for i in range(len(s)) if i not in hs)
```

#### 2nd approach

If you don't like hashtable, we can just construct an array to save the redundant parentheses and solve the problem in the same way

```py
"""
    2nd: similar logic without using a hashtable
	- 17 lines

    Time    O(3N)
    Space   O(N)
    244 ms, faster than 45.31%
"""


class Solution(object):
    def minRemoveToMakeValid(self, s):
        res, opens = [], []
        for i in range(len(s)):
            c = s[i]
            if c == '(':
                opens.append(i)
                res += c
            elif c == ')':
                if len(opens) == 0:
                    res += '*'
                else:
                    opens.pop()
                    res += c
            else:
                res += c
        for x in opens:
            res[x] = '*'
        return ''.join(c for c in res if c != '*')
```

