# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To solve this problem, you can use a two-pass approach:

1)First Pass - Remove Invalid Closing Parentheses: Iterate through the string from left to right and remove any closing parentheses ')' that don't have a matching opening parentheses '('. Keep track of the indices of these characters.

2)Second Pass - Remove Invalid Opening Parentheses: Iterate through the string from right to left. Similar to the first pass, remove any opening parentheses '(' that don't have a matching closing parentheses ')'. Keep track of the indices of these characters.

3)Building the Resultant String: After the two passes, you'll have the indices of characters that need to be removed to make the string valid. Construct a new string by excluding these characters.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1)First Pass - Remove Invalid Closing Parentheses:
Initialize an empty stack and a set to store the indices of characters to be removed.
Traverse through the string from left to right using the index i.
If s[i] is an opening parenthesis '(', push the index i onto the stack.
If s[i] is a closing parenthesis ')':
If the stack is empty, add the index i to the set of characters to be removed.
Otherwise, pop an index from the stack, indicating a valid match.
2)Second Pass - Remove Invalid Opening Parentheses:

Initialize an empty stack and a set to store the indices of characters to be removed.
Traverse through the string from right to left using the index i.
If s[i] is a closing parenthesis ')', push the index i onto the stack.
If s[i] is an opening parenthesis '(':
If the stack is empty, add the index i to the set of characters to be removed.
Otherwise, pop an index from the stack, indicating a valid match.
Build Resultant String:

3)Initialize an empty list to hold the characters of the resultant string.
Traverse through the string s using the index i.
If i is not in the set of characters to be removed, append s[i] to the resultant list.
Return Result:

Convert the list of characters to a string and return it.





# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
