class Solution {
public:
    string minRemoveToMakeValid(string s) {
        vector<int> v;
        string ans = "";
        int n = s.length();
        //try to match a open bracket, if not matching then it will be in the list 
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(s[i] == '(') v.push_back(i);
            else if(s[i] == ')'){
                if(v.size() > 0 && s[v.back()] == '(') v.pop_back();
                else v.push_back(i);
            }
        }
        //Now if any of the barces are not matched need to skip those from the string
        if(v.size() == 0) return s;
        for(int i = 0, j = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(j >= v.size() ) ans += s[i];
            else if(i != v[j]) ans += s[i];
            else j++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

```

solutions.content:
**Note that** the problem asks us to return **any valid string**, so that the only requirement is to remove the minimum number of parentheses.
There could be multiple answers, and this solution gives one of them that is easy to construct.

**The main idea is:**
If we loop through the input string from left to right, **it will be invalid** if at some position, **the number of ")" is larger than the number of "("**. When it becomes invalid, we will remove that character.
Besides, after the looping, all **"(" not yet matched (left in stack)** should also be removed.

**Initiate:**
**a stack** used to match "(" and ")".
**a set** that keeps the indexes of string that should be removed.

**Time:** O(n)
**Space:** O(n)

```
class Solution:
    def minRemoveToMakeValid(self, s: str) -> str:

        indexes_removed = set()
        stack = []

        for i, c in enumerate(s):
            if c not in "()":
                continue
            if c == "(":
                stack.append(i)
            else:
                if not stack:
                    indexes_removed.add(i)
                else:
                    stack.pop()

        stack_left = set(stack)
        indexes_removed = indexes_removed.union(stack_left)

        res = []
        for i, c in enumerate(s):
            if i in indexes_removed:
                continue
            res.append(c)

        return "".join(res)
```

