solutions.content:
Let's play from Alice's point of view. We want to maximize the difference between Alice's and Bob's scores. For any stone, suppose its value is a and b for Alice and Bob. 

1. If alice takes it, Alice's value will +a.
2. If alice does not take it, Bob's value will +b. From Alice's point of view, Alice's value will -b.

So for each stone, the difference by taking one of the above decisions can be as big as a + b. So we need to sort the stones so each time Alice/Bob just picks up the stone with the maximum a+b. This will make sure when Alice gets a, Bob will also lose b. The same strategy will apply to Bob as well.

```python
class Solution:
    def stoneGameVI(self, aliceValues: List[int], bobValues: List[int]) -> int:
        diff = [(a+b, i) for i, (a,b) in enumerate(zip(aliceValues, bobValues))]
        diff.sort(reverse=True)
        alice = bob = 0
        for i in range(len(diff)):
            if i % 2 == 0:
                alice += aliceValues[diff[i][1]]
            else:
                bob += bobValues[diff[i][1]]
        if alice > bob:
            return 1
        elif alice < bob:
            return -1
        else:
            return 0
```

