solutions.content:
Optimal strategy for both players at any point of time is to pick the stone with maximum combined value i.e. aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i] among all the remaining stones. Refer [Post 1](https://leetcode.com/problems/stone-game-vi/discuss/969635/math-proof) and [Post 2](https://leetcode.com/problems/stone-game-vi/discuss/969817/Strategy-proof) for great explanations of why that is the case.

**PriorityQueue**
```
// 139 ms. 26.61%
public int stoneGameVI(int[] aliceValues, int[] bobValues) {
    PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> Integer.compare(b[0] + b[1], a[0] + a[1]));
    for(int i = 0; i < aliceValues.length; i++) {
    	pq.add(new int[] { aliceValues[i], bobValues[i] });
    }
    int[] score = new int[2];
    for(int i = 0; i < aliceValues.length; i++) {
    	score[i & 1] += pq.poll()[i & 1];
    }
    return Integer.compare(score[0], score[1]);
}
```

Time complexity: O(n log n)
Space complexity: O(n)

**Sorting**

```
// 74 ms. 89.66%
public int stoneGameVI(int[] aliceValues, int[] bobValues) {
    int n = aliceValues.length;
    int[][] A = new int[n][];
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        A[i] = new int[] { aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i], aliceValues[i], bobValues[i] };
    }
    Arrays.sort(A, (a, b) -> b[0] - a[0]);
    int a = 0, b = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if((i & 1) == 0) {
            a += A[i][1];
        } else {
            b += A[i][2];
        }
    }
    return Integer.compare(a, b);
}
```

Time complexity: O(n log n)
Space complexity: O(n)

**Sorting - Space optimized**

```
// 15 ms. 99.50%
public int stoneGameVI(int[] aliceValues, int[] bobValues) {
    int n = aliceValues.length, diff = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        aliceValues[i] += bobValues[i];
        diff -= bobValues[i];
    }
    Arrays.sort(aliceValues);
    for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i -= 2) {
        diff += aliceValues[i];
    }
    return Integer.compare(diff, 0);
}
```

Time complexity: O(n log n)
Space complexity: O(1) assuming we're allowed to modify the original array(s) otherwise we'll need O(n).

**Counting sort**

```
// 3 ms. 100%
public int stoneGameVI(int[] aliceValues, int[] bobValues) {
    int n = aliceValues.length, diff = 0;
    int[] count = new int[201];
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        count[aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i]]++;
        diff -= bobValues[i];
    }
    for(int i = 200, turn = 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        diff += ((count[i] + turn) >> 1) * i;
        if((count[i] & 1) != 0) turn ^= 1;
    }
    return Integer.compare(diff, 0);
}
```

Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)

