solutions.content:
Inspired by [lee's solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/stone-game-vi/discuss/969574/JavaC%2B%2BPython-Sort-by-Value-Sum)

## Algorithm
We play the game a little backwards.
1. Assume that bob has taken all the tiles at once. So bobs points is `Sum(bobValues)`
2. Now, alice has `size/2` moves to play. Which stone she should pick? She should pick the one which
	* Maximizes her point
	* Minimizes bobs's point

In other words, should should pick the i such that `aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i]` is maximum.
As they will play optimally, alice can't take all the max values, she will take even numbered index to accomodate bob's optimum game.
If, after taking `size/2` values, alice should win if her taken values sum are greater than bob.

We can track this sum by taking a difference variable. 
First, `diff = -Sum(bobValues)`
Then, whenever index i is taken, diff is incremented `by aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i]`
if `diff > 0`, alice has won.

__Exmple__
```
aliceValues = [2,4,3]
bobValues = [1,6,7]
```

initially, bob gain points = `1 + 6 +7 = 14`
diff `= -14`
now, alice has available options `= 1+2, 4+6, 3+7 = 3, 10, 10`
													`= 10, 10, 3` (after sorting)

So, alice can take 10 and 3, makeing the differnce `= -14 + 13 = -1`, so she losts.
Taking first 10 = taking index 2 (or 3, same)
Taking second 1 = taking index 0

**Code**
```
int stoneGameVI(vector<int>& aliceValues, vector<int>& bobValues) {
	int diff = 0, n = aliceValues.size();

	for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
		aliceValues[i] += bobValues[i];
		diff -= bobValues[i];
	}

	sort(aliceValues.begin(), aliceValues.end());

	for(int i=n-1; i >= 0; i -= 2) {
		diff += aliceValues[i];
	}

	if (diff == 0) {
		return 0;
	}

	return diff < 0 ? -1 : 1;
}
```

