solutions.content:
## My comments on Greedy
I sometimes find other difficult topics like DP and backtracking easier compared to the Greedy class of problems. I managed to solve other Stone Game problems (before I solved this one) which were much more harder than this one. But Greedy problems can be elusive and this problem is evidence of that. I tried this problem for a long time. The problem with greedy problems is - you have to find the right strategy. Unlike DP and backtracking which are brute force methods. Greedy is purely about finding the shortcut. And it is hard to find shortcuts.

Best way to work around greedy problems is take the test cases and come  up with various strategies, 
in this particular problem I thought about various complicated ways that involved priority_queues to simulate best pick for both Alice and bob, but they just didn't work. 

## All about observation
Turns out it was a simple observation, which is you just evaluate how precious each stone is. i.e.  **how both Alice and Bob value each stone and sort them in descending order.** Then you just start picking in that order Alice first then Bob till you are done.

And that's it.


```
bool comp(const pair<int, int>& p1, const pair<int, int>& p2) {
    return p1.first > p2.first;
}


class Solution {
public:
    int stoneGameVI(vector<int>& aliceValues, vector<int>& bobValues) {

        int n = aliceValues.size();
        vector<pair<int, int>> precious;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            precious.push_back(make_pair(aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i], i));
        }

        sort(precious.begin(), precious.end(), comp); 
        int alice = 0, bob = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(i & 1)
                bob += bobValues[precious[i].second];
            else
                alice += aliceValues[precious[i].second];
        }

        if(alice > bob)
            return 1;
        if(alice < bob)
            return -1;
        return 0;
    }
};
```

