solutions.content:
The problem specifies that a given index in both arrays can only be used by either alice or bob.
The optimal way to play the game is to choose the maximum from whatever is options are available. 
What happens whaen we choose the maximum available option is, we are either taking the maximum from our array or eliminating the chance of our opponent to gather the point of a high scoring element.

Thus whoever has completed the game with maximum points after n/2 choices each wins.

We use a priority queue of pairs to store the sum at any given index and the index.
Beginning with alice we take the value at index from the priority queue and alternate turns.

```
int stoneGameVI(vector<int>& aliceValues, vector<int>& bobValues) {
	priority_queue<pair<int, int>> pq;
	for(int i = 0; i < bobValues.size(); i++){
		pq.push({aliceValues[i] + bobValues[i], i});
	}

	int bPoints = 0;
	int aPoints = 0;

	int turn = 1;
	while(!pq.empty()){
		if(turn){
			aPoints += aliceValues[pq.top().second];
		}
		else{
			bPoints += bobValues[pq.top().second];
		}

		turn = turn == 1 ? 0 : 1;
		pq.pop();
	}

	if(aPoints != bPoints)
		return aPoints > bPoints ? 1 : -1;

	return 0;
}
```

